				<div id=3D"bodyContent" class=3D"vector-body ve-init-mw-desktopArticleT=
arget-targetContainer" aria-labelledby=3D"firstHeading" data-mw-ve-target-c=
ontainer=3D"">
					<div class=3D"vector-body-before-content">
							<div class=3D"mw-indicators">
		</div>

						<div id=3D"siteSub" class=3D"noprint">From Wikipedia, the free encycl=
opedia</div>
					</div>
					<div id=3D"contentSub"><div id=3D"mw-content-subtitle"></div></div>
				=09
				=09
					<div id=3D"mw-content-text" class=3D"mw-body-content"><div class=3D"mw=
-content-ltr mw-parser-output" lang=3D"en" dir=3D"ltr"><div class=3D"shortd=
escription nomobile noexcerpt noprint searchaux" style=3D"display:none">Hit=
ting statistic in baseball</div>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:1939_Ted_Williams.png" class=3D"mw-file-descr=
iption"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/=
48/1939_Ted_Williams.png/250px-1939_Ted_Williams.png" decoding=3D"async" wi=
dth=3D"190" height=3D"262" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D"200=
6" data-file-height=3D"2767"></a><figcaption><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Ted_Williams" title=3D"Ted Williams">Ted Williams</a> is the all=
-time Major League Baseball leader in on-base percentage.</figcaption></fig=
ure>=20
<p>In <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Baseball_statistics" title=
=3D"Baseball statistics">baseball statistics</a>, <b>on-base percentage</b>=
 (<b>OBP</b>) measures how frequently a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Batting_(baseball)" title=3D"Batting (baseball)">batter</a> reaches <=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Base_(baseball)" class=3D"mw-redire=
ct" title=3D"Base (baseball)">base</a>. An official <a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Major_League_Baseball" title=3D"Major League Baseball">Ma=
jor League Baseball</a> (MLB) statistic since 1984, it is sometimes referre=
d to as <b>on-base average</b> (<b>OBA</b>),<sup id=3D"cite_ref-1" class=3D=
"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/On-base_percentage#cit=
e_note-1"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>a<span class=3D"cite-bracket=
">]</span></a></sup> as it is rarely presented as a true <a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Percentage" title=3D"Percentage">percentage</a>.
</p><p>Generally defined as "how frequently a batter reaches base per <a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Plate_appearance" title=3D"Plate appear=
ance">plate appearance</a>",<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Glossary_2-0" class=3D"refe=
rence"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/On-base_percentage#cite_not=
e-Glossary-2"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>1<span class=3D"cite-bra=
cket">]</span></a></sup> OBP is specifically calculated as the ratio of a b=
atter's <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Times_on_base" title=3D"Ti=
mes on base">times on base</a> (the sum of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Hit_(baseball)" title=3D"Hit (baseball)">hits</a>, <a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Base_on_balls" title=3D"Base on balls">bases on b=
alls</a>, and times <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hit_by_pitch" =
title=3D"Hit by pitch">hit by pitch</a>) to the sum of <a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/At_bat" title=3D"At bat">at bats</a>, bases on balls, =
hit by pitch, and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sacrifice_fly" t=
itle=3D"Sacrifice fly">sacrifice flies</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Glossary_2-1=
" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/On-base_perc=
entage#cite_note-Glossary-2"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>1<span cl=
ass=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> OBP does not credit the batter for =
reaching base on <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Error_(baseball)"=
 class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Error (baseball)">fielding errors</a>, <a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fielder%27s_choice" title=3D"Fielder's=
 choice">fielder's choice</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Unc=
aught_third_strike" title=3D"Uncaught third strike">uncaught third strikes<=
/a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Obstruction_(baseball)" title=
=3D"Obstruction (baseball)">fielder's obstruction</a>, or <a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Catcher%27s_interference" class=3D"mw-redirect" tit=
le=3D"Catcher's interference">catcher's interference</a>, and deducts from =
plate appearances a batter intentionally giving himself up in a <a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sacrifice_bunt" title=3D"Sacrifice bunt">sacr=
ifice bunt</a>.=20
</p><p>OBP is added to <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Slugging_av=
erage" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Slugging average">slugging average</a=
> (SLG) to determine <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/On-base_plus_=
slugging" title=3D"On-base plus slugging">on-base plus slugging</a> (OPS).=
=20
</p><p>The OBP of all batters faced by one pitcher or team is referred to a=
s "on-base against".
</p><p>On-base percentage is calculable for professional teams dating back =
to the first year of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/National_Asso=
ciation_of_Professional_Base_Ball_Players" title=3D"National Association of=
 Professional Base Ball Players">National Association of Professional Base =
Ball Players</a> competition in 1871,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-3" class=3D"refere=
nce"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/On-base_percentage#cite_note-=
3"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>2<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</sp=
an></a></sup> because the component values of its formula have been recorde=
d in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Box_score_(baseball)" title=
=3D"Box score (baseball)">box scores</a> ever since.=20
</p>
<meta property=3D"mw:PageProp/toc">
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"History">History</h2><span =
class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DOn-base_percentage&amp=
;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D1" title=3D"Edit section: History"><span>edit<=
/span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>The statistic was invented in the late 1940s by <a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Brooklyn_Dodgers" title=3D"Brooklyn Dodgers">Brooklyn Dodg=
ers</a> statistician <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Allan_Roth" t=
itle=3D"Allan Roth">Allan Roth</a> with then-Dodgers general manager <a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Branch_Rickey" title=3D"Branch Rickey">B=
ranch Rickey</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-4" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/On-base_percentage#cite_note-4"><span class=3D"ci=
te-bracket">[</span>3<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=
=3D"cite_ref-5" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/On-base_percentage#cite_note-5"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>4<sp=
an class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> In 1954, Rickey, who was then =
the general manager of the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pittsbu=
rgh_Pirates" title=3D"Pittsburgh Pirates">Pittsburgh Pirates</a>, was featu=
red in a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Life_(magazine)" title=3D=
"Life (magazine)">Life Magazine</a> graphic in which the formula for on-bas=
e percentage was shown as the first component of an all-encompassing "offen=
se" equation.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-6" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/On-base_percentage#cite_note-6"><span class=3D"cite-b=
racket">[</span>5<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> However, i=
t was not named as on-base percentage, and there is little evidence that Ro=
th's statistic was taken seriously at the time by the baseball community at=
 large.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-7" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/On-base_percentage#cite_note-7"><span class=3D"cite-bracket=
">[</span>6<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>On-base percentage became an official MLB statistic in 1984. Its per=
ceived importance jumped after the influential 2003 book <i><a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Moneyball:_The_Art_of_Winning_an_Unfair_Game" tit=
le=3D"Moneyball: The Art of Winning an Unfair Game">Moneyball</a></i> highl=
ighted <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Oakland_Athletics" title=3D=
"Oakland Athletics">Oakland Athletics</a> general manager <a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Billy_Beane" title=3D"Billy Beane">Billy Beane</a>'=
s focus on the statistic.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-8" class=3D"reference"><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/On-base_percentage#cite_note-8"><span cla=
ss=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>7<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup=
> Many baseball observers, particularly those influenced by the field of <a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sabermetrics" title=3D"Sabermetrics"=
>sabermetrics</a>, now consider on-base percentage superior to the  statist=
ic traditionally used to measure offensive skill, <a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Batting_average_(baseball)" title=3D"Batting average (baseb=
all)">batting average</a>,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-9" class=3D"reference"><a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/On-base_percentage#cite_note-9"><span cl=
ass=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>8<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></su=
p><sup id=3D"cite_ref-10" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/On-base_percentage#cite_note-10"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[=
</span>9<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> which accounts for =
hits but ignores other ways a batter can reach base.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-11"=
 class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/On-base_perce=
ntage#cite_note-11"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>10<span class=3D"c=
ite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Overview">Overview</h2><spa=
n class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DOn-base_percentage&a=
mp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D2" title=3D"Edit section: Overview"><span>ed=
it</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>Traditionally, players with the best on-base percentages bat as <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Leadoff_hitter" title=3D"Leadoff hitter">=
leadoff hitter</a>, unless they are power hitters, who traditionally bat sl=
ightly lower in the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Batting_order_=
(baseball)" title=3D"Batting order (baseball)">batting order</a>. The leagu=
e average for on-base percentage in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/Major_League_Baseball" title=3D"Major League Baseball">Major League Baseb=
all</a> has varied considerably over time; at its peak in the late 1990s, i=
t was around .340, whereas it was typically .300 during the <a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dead-ball_era" title=3D"Dead-ball era">dead-ball =
era</a>. On-base percentage can also vary quite considerably from player to=
 player. The highest career OBP of a batter with more than 3,000 <a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Plate_appearance" title=3D"Plate appearance"=
>plate appearances</a> is .482 by <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Ted_Williams" title=3D"Ted Williams">Ted Williams</a>. The lowest is by <a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bill_Bergen" title=3D"Bill Bergen">Bi=
ll Bergen</a>, who had an OBP of .194.
</p><p>On-base percentage is calculated using this formula:<sup id=3D"cite_=
ref-12" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/On-bas=
e_percentage#cite_note-12"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>11<span cla=
ss=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-13" class=3D"refe=
rence"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/On-base_percentage#cite_not=
e-13"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>12<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]=
</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-fangraphs_14-0" class=3D"reference"><a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/On-base_percentage#cite_note-fangrap=
hs-14"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>13<span class=3D"cite-bracket">=
]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<dl><dd><span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-inline"><span clas=
s=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;">=
<math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\displaystyl=
e OBP=3D{\frac {H+BB+HBP}{AB+BB+HBP+SF}}}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle=3D"true" scriptlevel=3D"0">
        <mi>O</mi>
        <mi>B</mi>
        <mi>P</mi>
        <mo>=3D</mo>
        <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
          <mfrac>
            <mrow>
              <mi>H</mi>
              <mo>+</mo>
              <mi>B</mi>
              <mi>B</mi>
              <mo>+</mo>
              <mi>H</mi>
              <mi>B</mi>
              <mi>P</mi>
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              <mi>A</mi>
              <mi>B</mi>
              <mo>+</mo>
              <mi>B</mi>
              <mi>B</mi>
              <mo>+</mo>
              <mi>H</mi>
              <mi>B</mi>
              <mi>P</mi>
              <mo>+</mo>
              <mi>S</mi>
              <mi>F</mi>
            </mrow>
          </mfrac>
        </mrow>
      </mstyle>
    </mrow>
    <annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">{\displaystyle OBP=3D{\frac =
{H+BB+HBP}{AB+BB+HBP+SF}}}</annotation>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src=3D"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/rend=
er/svg/d497b106820c509fa8baa93f3c42cc5087fb0fea" class=3D"mwe-math-fallback=
-image-inline mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertical=
-align: -2.171ex; width:33.587ex; height:5.509ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle OB=
P=3D{\frac {H+BB+HBP}{AB+BB+HBP+SF}}}"></span></dd></dl>
<p>where
</p>
<ul><li><i>H</i> =3D <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hit_(baseball=
)" title=3D"Hit (baseball)">Hits</a></li>
<li><i>BB</i> =3D <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Base_on_balls" t=
itle=3D"Base on balls">Bases on Balls (Walks)</a></li>
<li><i>HBP</i> =3D <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hit_by_pitch" t=
itle=3D"Hit by pitch">Hit By Pitch</a></li>
<li><i>AB</i> =3D <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/At_bat" title=3D=
"At bat">At bat</a></li>
<li><i>SF</i> =3D <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sacrifice_fly" t=
itle=3D"Sacrifice fly">Sacrifice fly</a></li></ul>
<p>In certain unofficial calculations, the denominator is simplified and re=
placed by <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Plate_appearance" title=
=3D"Plate appearance">Plate Appearance</a> (PA); however, the calculation P=
As includes certain infrequent events that will slightly lower the calculat=
ed OBP (i.e. <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Catcher%27s_interfere=
nce" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Catcher's interference">catcher's inter=
ference</a>, and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sacrifice_bunt" t=
itle=3D"Sacrifice bunt">sacrifice bunts</a>).<sup id=3D"cite_ref-fangraphs_=
14-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/On-base_=
percentage#cite_note-fangraphs-14"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>13<=
span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Sacrifice bunts are excluded=
 from consideration on the basis that they are usually imposed by the manag=
er with the expectation that the batter will not reach base, and thus do no=
t accurately reflect the batter's ability to reach base when attempting to =
do so. This is in contrast with the sacrifice fly, which is generally unint=
entional; the batter was trying for a hit.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Glossary_2-2"=
 class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/On-base_perce=
ntage#cite_note-Glossary-2"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>1<span cla=
ss=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
